    "title": "LESSON 6: GRIMM'S LAW",
    "header_color": "magenta",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 2,
        "content": [
          "   In 1822 Jacob Grimm — yes, that Grimm,",
          "   the fairy tale one — noticed something.",
          "   Latin and Germanic words for the same",
          "   thing were related, but the consonants",
          "   had shifted. Not at random. In a pattern.",
          "",
          "   Latin p became Germanic f.",
          "     pater → father",
          "     piscis → fish",
          "     pes → foot",
          "",
          "   Latin t became Germanic th.",
          "     tres → three",
          "     tu → thou",
          "",
          "   Latin k (c) became Germanic h.",
          "     cornu → horn",
          "     canis → hound"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Lesson 6",
        "pronunciation_mappings": {}
      },
      {
        "page": 2,
        "total_pages": 2,
        "content": [
          "   Once you see Grimm's Law, you can't",
          "   stop seeing it. Every cognate pair",
          "   between a Romance language and a",
          "   Germanic one rides these rails.",
          "",
          "   Spanish 'pie' and English 'foot'?",
          "   Same word, 3000 years ago.",
          "   French 'cœur' and English 'heart'?",
          "   Same word. k became h.",
          "",
          "   This cluster walks you through the",
          "   most striking pairs. The goal isn't",
          "   memorisation — it's recognition.",
          "",
          "   You're not learning new words here.",
          "   You're seeing old ones clearly for",
          "   the first time."
        ],
        "pronunciation_mappings": {}
